    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA343-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu talaimakaṉ piriviṭai āṟṟāḷāyc colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what [SHE] said when being unable to bear it in the time HE had separated.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA343">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>          mullai tāya kallatarc ciṟuneṟi</l>
<l>          yaṭaiyā tiṟanta vaṅkuṭic cīṟūrt</l>
<l>          tāteru maṟuki ṉāpuṟan tīṇṭu</l>
<l>          neṭuvī ḻiṭṭa kaṭavu ḷālat</l>
<l>          tukupali yaruntiya tokuviraṟ kākkai</l>
<l>          puṉka ṇantik kiḷaivayiṟ ceṟiyap</l>
<l>          paṭaiyoṭu vanta paiyuṇ mālai</l>
<l>          yillaikol vāḻi tōḻi nattuṟan</l>
<l>          tarumporuṭ kūṭṭam vēṇṭip</l>
<l>          pirintuṟai kātalar ceṉṟa nāṭṭē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Are there not, oh friend,</l>
<l>sorrowful evenings, come with [all their] weapons,</l>
<l rend="indent">when the crows with greedy(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">toku viral</term>: T.V.G. understands this as a physical description, referring to the close-set toes of the bird, but to me it seems more plausible to read it, in a transferred sense, as a description of its habits.</note> fingers that had eaten from the offering</l>
<l rend="indent2">            shed at the god’s Banyan tree, placed within the long aerial roots</l>
<l rend="indent3">            touching the back of the cows by the street in the fine(?) dung<note place="foot">For <term xml:lang="ta">tātēru</term> see also KT 46 - which is in every way a cognate in structure and topic.</note></l>
<l rend="indent4">            in the small village with pretty homes [he] traversed without joy,</l>
<l rend="indent3">            on the small path of stones [and] fine sand spread with jasmine,</l>
<l rend="indent">            are close to [their] relations in the sorrowful twilight,</l>
<l>          – in the land [our] lover has gone to, remaining separate,</l>
<l rend="indent2">            wanting union<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kūṭṭam</term>: it is difficult to tell whether the word is used here in one of its more neutral connotations or whether it is employed on purpose here. Since it refers to the union of lovers, it might well mean HER indicating that HE has made an erotic choice (loving wealth, not her).</note> with difficult wealth, abandoning us?</l>
      </lg>
      </div>
